I’m a strong believer in yesterday’s home runs don’t win today’s games. BUT. With that said, today I took home a birthday chip, marking my one year of sobriety. This post is to be of service to those who find themselves entertaining the idea of sobriety…each one, teach one. if I can do it, you can do it. There is nothing special about me, I am just as human as you are…people will scoff at you, they will give back handed comments, and they will ridicule you for wanting to better yourself. When you find yourself in this position, know that you are exactly where you are suppose to be.  Keep going. You will find your tribe. You will find your people.

Bryan Black is a SoCal surfing tattoo artist with a big heart. He opened up about his recovery status on Paramount+’s Ink Master, so I hit him up for a chill conversation. On this Thanksgiving episode (literally recorded right before we smashed turkey & pie), we talk about gratitude, memorable tattoos, the transformative power of love from strangers, and our imperative to roll deep on this recovery journey. This is the first tattoo machine I’ve ever built for myself with help from my mentor  @timhendricks everything was made and assembled by hand from start to finish, the side plate was cut and filed by hand, and the coils were wound by yours truly. 

If I were to give any advice to any younger tattooer or anyone in pursuit of their dreams, it would be what Craig Stecyk ( hard name drop ) told me in passing. “ enjoy the process, enjoy the ride “. comparison is the thief of joy, you are exactly where you are suppose to be. So Be nice to yourself and Try to detach yourself from those who can’t comprehend your journey, it’s not for them to understand. 

Swipe left for the first bundle of needles I’ve ever made for myself, and still till this day is my favorite grouping. And actual footage of Tim and I working in the machine shop together

It’s been a few years since I traded late nights for early mornings and it’s made a significant difference in my overall mental health, productivity, and happiness. This meant less partying, less drinking, etc etc.

While I’m not sober, I do love Bryan’s perspective on this.

How many habits are you holding on to that don’t serve any of your goals? What can you change so that your actions match to your ambitions?

Maybe it’s not alcohol, but maybe it’s those two hours in front of the TV every day, or hanging with people who don’t align with your values. Maybe it’s choosing to stay with someone more concerned about keeping you the same for their sake rather than helping you grow.

There are so many things that hold us back that we don’t even recognize because we’re too comfortable with the routine of it all. The new year is typically a symbol of a fresh start, so why not try something different today?

#sober #2024 #goalsetting #sobercurious
